**Elasticsearch version** (`bin/elasticsearch --version`): 7.11.1

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:

The API responds with a different key in the payload, depending if buckets exist or the list is empty. 

In case of existing buckets the payload is represented as 
```
{
  "count": 1,
  "overall_buckets": [
        {
          "timestamp": 1464742800000,
          "bucket_span": 3600,
          "overall_score": 0,
          "jobs": [
            {
              "job_id": "jobs-get-result-overall-buckets-17",
              "max_anomaly_score": 0
            },
            {
              "job_id": "jobs-get-result-overall-buckets-30",
              "max_anomaly_score": 0
            },
            {
              "job_id": "jobs-get-result-overall-buckets-60",
              "max_anomaly_score": 0
            }
          ],
          "is_interim": false,
          "result_type": "overall_bucket"
        }
      ]
    }
```
see the integration tests: https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/blob/master/x-pack/plugin/src/yamlRestTest/resources/rest-api-spec/test/ml/jobs_get_result_overall_buckets.yml#L283

If the result is **0**, the key `overall_buckets` is no longer present and replaced by `jobs`, e.g.
```
{
  "count" : 0,
  "jobs" : [ ]
}
```
Furthermore do the integration tests not cover this case and solely check for the value of `count` but not the existence of `overall_buckets` or its value.

**Steps to reproduce**:
Integration test or run `GET _ml/anomaly_detectors/none-matching-*/results/overall_buckets`

